{"title_page": "Robert Sheffield", "text_new": "{{short description|English Speaker of the House of Commons}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2016}}\n{{ infobox nobility\n| name         = Sir Robert Sheffield\n| image        = \n| caption      = \n| father       = Sir Robert Sheffield\n| mother       = Jane Lounde\n| spouse       = Ellen Delves<br>Anne Barley\n| issue        = Robert Sheffield<br>four daughters\n| birth_date   = before 1462\n| birth_place  = \n| death_date   = 10 August 1518\n| death_place  = \n}}\n\n'''Sir Robert Sheffield''' (before 1462 \u2013 10 August 1518) was an English lawyer and Member of Parliament. He was [[Speaker of the House of Commons (United Kingdom)|Speaker of the House of Commons]] between 1512\u20131513.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.parliament.uk/documents/commons/lib/research/briefings/snpc-04637.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=2 December 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111122025529/http://www.parliament.uk/documents/commons/lib/research/briefings/snpc-04637.pdf |archive-date=22 November 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Family==\nRobert Sheffield was the son of Sir Robert Sheffield of [[South Cave]], [[Yorkshire]], by Jane Lounde, the daughter and coheir of Alexander Lownde of [[Butterwick, Lincolnshire]].{{sfn|Lock|2004}}\n\n==Career==\nHe was trained in the law at the [[Inner Temple]], and became Governor of the Inner Temple in 1511. He served as [[Recorder of London]] from 1495 to 1508, and was thus an ''ex officio'' [[Member of Parliament]] for the [[City of London (UK Parliament constituency)|City of London]] in 1495, 1497 and 1504. [[Bernard Andreas]] states that Sheffield resigned the recordership in April 1508.\n\nHe was a commander at [[Battle of Blackheath|Blackheath]] during the [[Cornish Rebellion of 1497]], and knighted by [[Henry VII of England|Henry VII]] after the battle.\n\nSheffield was chosen [[Knights of the shire|Knight of the Shire]] for [[Lincolnshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Lincolnshire]] in 1512 and 1513. During these years, he served as [[List of Speakers of the House of Commons of England|Speaker of the House of Commons]].<ref name=history>{{cite web|url=http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1509-1558/member/sheffield-sir-robert-1462-1518|title=SHEFFIELD, Sir Robert (by 1462-1518), of the Inner Temple, London, West Butterwick, Lincs. and Chilwell, Notts. - History of Parliament Online|website=Historyofparliamentonline.org|accessdate=1 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 1515, Sheffield helped [[Thomas Wolsey|Cardinal Wolsey]] in drafting legislation but later gave lead to [[anti-clericalism|anti-clerical]] forces in the House, earning him the Cardinal's enmity. In 1516, he was charged with negligence as a justice of the peace and was summoned before the [[Star Chamber]] but negotiated a pardon. Six months later he was incarcerated in the [[Tower of London]] after complaining against [[Thomas Wolsey|Cardinal Wolsey]], and brought before the Star Chamber again, and this time asked the King for mercy. However the pardon was revoked and he died in the [[Tower of London]] on 10 August 1518.  He was buried in the Augustinian church (Blackfriars), London.<ref name=\"history\"/> His will is in ''Testamenta Vetusta'' by [[Nicholas Harris Nicolas]] (p.&nbsp;555).\n\n==Marriages and issue==\nSheffield married firstly Ellen Delves, the daughter and heir of [[Delves baronets|Sir John Delves]] of [[Doddington, Cheshire]], by whom he had a son and heir, Robert Sheffield (d.1531), who married Jane Stanley, daughter of [[George Stanley, 9th Baron Strange]], and sister of [[Thomas Stanley, 2nd Earl of Derby]], and four daughters. Edmund Sheffield, the son of Robert Sheffield (d.1531) and Jane Stanley, became first [[Baron Sheffield]] in 1547.\n\nAfter his first wife's death in or after 1509, Sheffield married secondly Anne Barley or Barlee (d. 1557 or 1558), the daughter of William Barley, of [[Albury, Hertfordshire]]. After Sheffield's death in 1518 his widow married secondly Sir John Grey of [[Blisworth]], [[Northamptonshire]], a younger son of [[Thomas Grey, 1st Marquess of Dorset]] by his second wife, [[Cecily Bonville, 7th Baroness Harington|Cecily Bonville]], and thirdly Sir Richard Clement, of [[Ightham Mote]], [[Kent]]. Anne (n\u00e9e Barlee) left a will dated 1 October 1557, proved 7 May 1558.{{sfn|Challen|1963|pp=5-9}}{{sfn|Richardson II|2011|pp=304-6}}{{sfn|Lock|2004}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Sheffield baronets]], including other persons called \"Sir Robert Sheffield\"\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*{{Cite journal |last=Challen |first=W.H. |date=January 1963 |title=Lady Anne Grey |journal=Notes and Queries |volume=10 |issue=1 |pages=5\u20139 |url=http://nq.oxfordjournals.org/content/10/1.toc |accessdate=12 June 2013 |ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite ODNB |last=Lock |first=Julian |year=2004 |title=Sheffield, Sir Robert (b. before 1462, d. 1518) |id=25299}}  {{DNBfirst|wstitle=Sheffield, Robert}}\n*{{Cite book |last=Richardson |first=Douglas |year=2011 |title=Magna Carta Ancestry: A Study in Colonial and Medieval Families |editor-first=Kimball G. |editor-last=Everingham |location=Salt Lake City |edition=2nd |volume=II |pages=304\u20136 |ref={{sfnref |Richardson II |2011}} |isbn=978-1449966386 }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box | title=[[List of Speakers of the House of Commons of England|Speaker of the House of Commons]] | before=[[Thomas Englefield|Sir Thomas Englefield]] | after=[[Thomas Nevill]]| years=1512\u20131513}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Speaker of the British House of Commons}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sheffield, Robert}}\n[[Category:15th-century births]]\n[[Category:1518 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from the Borough of Boston]]\n[[Category:People from South Cave]]\n[[Category:Prisoners in the Tower of London]]\n[[Category:Speakers of the House of Commons of England]]\n[[Category:16th-century English lawyers]]\n[[Category:Recorders of London]]\n[[Category:People of the Tudor period]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of England for the City of London]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1495]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1497]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1504]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1512\u20131514]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1515]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|English Speaker of the House of Commons}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2016}}\n{{ infobox nobility\n| name         = Sir Robert Sheffield\n| image        = \n| caption      = \n| father       = Sir Robert Sheffield\n| mother       = Jane Lounde\n| spouse       = Ellen Delves<br>Anne Barley\n| issue        = Robert Sheffield<br>four daughters\n| birth_date   = before 1462\n| birth_place  = \n| death_date   = 10 August 1518\n| death_place  = \n}}\n\n'''Sir Robert Sheffield''' (before 1462 \u2013 10 August 1518) was an English lawyer and Member of Parliament. He was [[Speaker of the House of Commons (United Kingdom)|Speaker of the House of Commons]] between 1512-1513.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.parliament.uk/documents/commons/lib/research/briefings/snpc-04637.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=2 December 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111122025529/http://www.parliament.uk/documents/commons/lib/research/briefings/snpc-04637.pdf |archive-date=22 November 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Family==\nRobert Sheffield was the son of Sir Robert Sheffield of [[South Cave]], [[Yorkshire]], by Jane Lounde, the daughter and coheir of Alexander Lownde of [[Butterwick, Lincolnshire]].{{sfn|Lock|2004}}\n\n==Career==\nHe was trained in the law at the [[Inner Temple]], and became Governor of the Inner Temple in 1511. He served as [[Recorder of London]] from 1495 to 1508, and was thus an ''ex officio'' [[Member of Parliament]] for the [[City of London (UK Parliament constituency)|City of London]] in 1495, 1497 and 1504. [[Bernard Andreas]] states that Sheffield resigned the recordership in April 1508.\n\nHe was a commander at [[Battle of Blackheath|Blackheath]] during the [[Cornish Rebellion of 1497]], and knighted by [[Henry VII of England|Henry VII]] after the battle.\n\nSheffield was chosen [[Knights of the shire|Knight of the Shire]] for [[Lincolnshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Lincolnshire]] in 1512 and 1513. During these years, he served as [[List of Speakers of the House of Commons of England|Speaker of the House of Commons]].<ref name=history>{{cite web|url=http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1509-1558/member/sheffield-sir-robert-1462-1518|title=SHEFFIELD, Sir Robert (by 1462-1518), of the Inner Temple, London, West Butterwick, Lincs. and Chilwell, Notts. - History of Parliament Online|website=Historyofparliamentonline.org|accessdate=1 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 1515, Sheffield helped [[Thomas Wolsey|Cardinal Wolsey]] in drafting legislation but later gave lead to [[anti-clericalism|anti-clerical]] forces in the House, earning him the Cardinal's enmity. In 1516, he was charged with negligence as a justice of the peace and was summoned before the [[Star Chamber]] but negotiated a pardon. Six months later he was incarcerated in the [[Tower of London]] after complaining against [[Thomas Wolsey|Cardinal Wolsey]], and brought before the Star Chamber again, and this time asked the King for mercy. However the pardon was revoked and he died in the [[Tower of London]] on 10 August 1518.  He was buried in the Augustinian church (Blackfriars), London.<ref name=\"history\"/> His will is in ''Testamenta Vetusta'' by [[Nicholas Harris Nicolas]] (p.&nbsp;555).\n\n==Marriages and issue==\nSheffield married firstly Ellen Delves, the daughter and heir of [[Delves baronets|Sir John Delves]] of [[Doddington, Cheshire]], by whom he had a son and heir, Robert Sheffield (d.1531), who married Jane Stanley, daughter of [[George Stanley, 9th Baron Strange]], and sister of [[Thomas Stanley, 2nd Earl of Derby]], and four daughters. Edmund Sheffield, the son of Robert Sheffield (d.1531) and Jane Stanley, became first [[Baron Sheffield]] in 1547.\n\nAfter his first wife's death in or after 1509, Sheffield married secondly Anne Barley or Barlee (d. 1557 or 1558), the daughter of William Barley, of [[Albury, Hertfordshire]]. After Sheffield's death in 1518 his widow married secondly Sir John Grey of [[Blisworth]], [[Northamptonshire]], a younger son of [[Thomas Grey, 1st Marquess of Dorset]] by his second wife, [[Cecily Bonville, 7th Baroness Harington|Cecily Bonville]], and thirdly Sir Richard Clement, of [[Ightham Mote]], [[Kent]]. Anne (n\u00e9e Barlee) left a will dated 1 October 1557, proved 7 May 1558.{{sfn|Challen|1963|pp=5-9}}{{sfn|Richardson II|2011|pp=304-6}}{{sfn|Lock|2004}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Sheffield baronets]], including other persons called \"Sir Robert Sheffield\"\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*{{Cite journal |last=Challen |first=W.H. |date=January 1963 |title=Lady Anne Grey |journal=Notes and Queries |volume=10 |issue=1 |pages=5\u20139 |url=http://nq.oxfordjournals.org/content/10/1.toc |accessdate=12 June 2013 |ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite ODNB |last=Lock |first=Julian |year=2004 |title=Sheffield, Sir Robert (b. before 1462, d. 1518) |id=25299}}  {{DNBfirst|wstitle=Sheffield, Robert}}\n*{{Cite book |last=Richardson |first=Douglas |year=2011 |title=Magna Carta Ancestry: A Study in Colonial and Medieval Families |editor-first=Kimball G. |editor-last=Everingham |location=Salt Lake City |edition=2nd |volume=II |pages=304\u20136 |ref={{sfnref |Richardson II |2011}} |isbn=978-1449966386 }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box | title=[[List of Speakers of the House of Commons of England|Speaker of the House of Commons]] | before=[[Thomas Englefield|Sir Thomas Englefield]] | after=[[Thomas Nevill]]| years=1512\u20131513}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Speaker of the British House of Commons}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sheffield, Robert}}\n[[Category:15th-century births]]\n[[Ca